 United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":24,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":55,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William FitzThomas was born about 1235, in Emley, Yorkshire, England, his father, William FitzThomas Sr., was 23 and his mother, Agnes de Grey, was 25. He had at least 1 son with Lady William FitzWilliam. He died in 1295, in Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 61."},"et":{"abt 1235–1295":"umbes 1235–1295","1235–1295":"1235–1295","1217–1250":"1217–1250","1200–Female":"1200–Surnud","1254–1338":"1254–1338","1258–1294":"1258–1294","1214–1294":"1214–1294","1212–Female":"1212–Surnud","Abt 1258":"umbes 1258","1295":"1295","About 1255":"umbes 125